# Text formatting

## Normal writing

As simple as writing normally
:::code
this is normal text
:::

Example:
this is normal text

## Headers
The headers go from h1 to h6, h1 is bigger than h2 that is bigger than h3...

:::note
The first h1 in your mmx file will be the title of the page
:::


A header is declared in a new line like in markdown:

:::code
# This is a h1
## This is a h2
### This is a h3
#### This is a h4
##### This is a h5
###### This is a h6
:::

:::note
It's highly recomended to only use a single h1 and as many as you want h2, h3, h4, h5, h6.
:::

You can optionaly put after the header declaration a tag to the header for going to that header with a link
:::code
# This is a h1 with a tag %{tag}%
## This is a h2 with a tag %{Anothertag}%
### This is a h3 with a tag %{Anothertag2}%
#### This is a h4 with a tag %{Anothertag3}%
##### This is a h5 with a tag %{Anothertag4}%
###### This is a h6 with a tag %{Anothertag5}%
:::

To go to a header with a tag is as simple as writing a link with like this: `[Header](#id)` or to go to a header in another page:
`[Header](pages/the/Page/You/Want/To/Go.html#id)`

[Here](pages/Examples/Headers example.html) are some examples


## Enters
In mmx writing normally the enters only works if they are dividing two paragraphs, a enter to maka a blank line will not work for that there is the `#b` element.
This element only works at the start of the line and with nothing more in the same line
:::code
#b
:::

Here's an example of 3 `#b`

#b
#b
#b

## Coloured text

In mmx you can color text with a html style sintax with html supported color formats like hex, rgb or color names:
:::code
<c="color">Text in that color</c>
<c="red">This text will be coloured in red</c>
<c="blue">This text will be coloured in blue</c>
<c="#ffcc40">This text will be coloured in yellow</c>
<c="rgb(130, 130, 130)">This text will be coloured in gray</c>
:::

Examples
<c="color">Text in that color </c><c="red">This text will be coloured in red</c> normal text <c="blue">This text will be coloured in blue</c><c="#ffcc40"> This text will be coloured in yellow</c> <c="rgb(130, 130, 130)"> This text will be coloured in gray</c>

## Separators
A simple separator
This element `#s` only works at the start of the line and with nothing more in the same line like the `#b`

:::code
#s
:::

Example:
#s


## Inline code
Inline code is declared with
:::code
`code`
:::
and keeps the code from be processed by the parser, it has monospaced typografy and a background

Example:

`This is some inline code, this dont works inside me: [Header](pages/the/Page/You/Want/To/Go.html#id)`

## Notes
A note is a piece of text that appears with te text note and a background

#code(assets/code/note.txt)

Example:

:::note
This is a note
:::